The general environment to which the concrete will be exposed during its working life is classified into five levels of severity — Mild, Moderate, Severe, Very severe, and Extreme — as described in Table 3 (environmental exposure conditions). The exposure-class axis defined here is the key categorical input feeding into:
  • Table 5 (minimum cement content, maximum free water-cement ratio, minimum grade of concrete) — clause 8.2.4.1;
  • Table 16 (nominal cover to meet durability requirements) — clause 26.4.2;
  • the surface-crack-width limits in clause 35.3.2 (0.3 mm general / 0.2 mm cracking-harmful / 0.1 mm severe-environment).

Clause 8.2.2.2 (abrasive) — specialist literature may be referred to for durability requirements of concrete surfaces exposed to abrasive action, for example in the case of machinery and metal tyres. The abrasive exposure category is outside the five-level scheme of Table 3 because abrasion is a mechanical wear mechanism rather than a chemical or environmental ingress mechanism; the routine exposure-class lookup does not address it.

To avoid confusion and error in batching, consideration should be given to using the smallest practical number of different concrete mixes on any site or in any one plant. In batching concrete:

— the quantity of both cement and aggregate shall be determined by mass;
— admixture, if solid, by mass;
— liquid admixture may be measured by volume or mass;
— water shall be weighed or measured by volume in a calibrated tank (see also IS 4925).

Read-mixed concrete supplied by ready-mixed concrete (RMC) plant shall be preferred. For large and medium project sites, the concrete shall be sourced from ready-mixed concrete plants or from captive on-site or off-site automatic batching and mixing plants. The concrete produced and supplied by ready-mixed concrete plants shall be in accordance with IS 4926. In case of concrete from captive on-site or off-site automatic batching and mixing plants, similar quality control shall be followed.

(10.2.4) Volume batching may be allowed only where weigh-batching is not practical, and only provided accurate bulk densities of the materials to be actually used in concrete have earlier been established. Allowance for bulking shall be made in accordance with IS 2386 (Part 3). The mass-volume relationship shall be checked as frequently as necessary; the frequency for the given job shall be determined by the engineer-in-charge to ensure that the specified grading is maintained.

(10.2.6) No substitutions in materials used on the work, or alterations in the established proportions — except as permitted in 10.2.4 (volume batching with established bulk densities) and 10.2.5 (moisture-content adjustments) — shall be made without additional tests to show that the quality and strength of concrete are satisfactory.

It is important to maintain the water-cement ratio constant at its correct value. To this end:

— determination of moisture contents in both fine and coarse aggregates shall be made as frequently as possible, the frequency for a given job being determined by the engineer-in-charge according to weather conditions;
— the amount of added water shall be adjusted to compensate for any observed variations in the moisture contents (refer IS 2386 Part 3 for the determination procedure);
— suitable adjustments in the masses of aggregates shall also be made to allow for variation in mass due to moisture variation;
— where batching plants are used, it is recommended to determine moisture content by moisture probes fitted to the batching plants.

In the absence of exact data, and only in the case of nominal mixes, the amount of surface water may be estimated from the values given in Table 10.

The rule keeps the design w/c ratio constant as a single number while letting the as-measured water (added at the batcher) and the as-batched aggregate mass fluctuate together with moisture. This is the only sanctioned mechanism for handling the routine moisture variation of stockpiled aggregates; the alternative — leaving added water constant and accepting w/c drift — is implicitly disallowed by the constancy mandate.

Dosages of retarders, plasticizers, and superplasticizers shall be restricted to:

— 0.5 percent (retarders);
— 1.0 percent (plasticizers);
— 2.0 percent (superplasticizers);

respectively, by mass of cementitious materials. However, the dosages of polycarboxylate-based admixtures shall not exceed 1.0 percent.

A higher value of the above admixtures may be used if agreed upon between the manufacturer and the constructor, based on performance tests relating to workability, setting time, and early-age strength.

The rule binds two separate ceilings: a chemistry-by-function ceiling on the three traditional admixture categories (retarders / plasticizers / superplasticizers), and a chemistry-by-class ceiling on polycarboxylate-based admixtures specifically. Polycarboxylate ethers are the high-range water reducers most commonly classified as superplasticizers but, by their potency and the risk of over-dosing leading to retardation or segregation, the code caps their dosage at 1.0 percent — half the 2.0 percent ceiling that would otherwise apply by function. The performance-test exception applies to all four ceilings but requires agreement between manufacturer and constructor and is tied to the three named performance outcomes (workability, setting time, early-age strength).
